text: The results are in! Who ate the most sausages? Which state had the happiest voters? Our wrap of the federal election: http://t.co/8Ujq1egiHV
Correction: Tasmanians were the voters who most enjoyed themselves, with over EIGHTY percent saying they would vote at the same booth again.
We've got a lot of numbers to crunch, so we'll back tomorrow with the full digest.
The most popular polling booth was at Brunswick East Primary, with nineteen voters all saying they would vote there again!
We received international reviews from eight different countries on three different continents.
Queenslanders saw the most politicians, and voters in the ACT had the best chances of getting a sausage or a cake.
Victoria was our biggest state, with over four hundred reviews.
All up we received nearly fifteen hundred reviews, from over a thousand different polling places across Australia and the world.
That's it! We'd like to thank everyone who contributed a review of their voting experience, the response has exceeded all our expectations.
If you haven't reviewed your election experience yet, we're keeping submissions open until eight o'clock tonight. http://t.co/dOLkGXKX0G
Results are now rolling in; our thanks to @abcnews for their support today, as well as @byteintoit and @switchelections for having us on.

Correction to those earlier figures: excluding double-ups, we received 156 reviews from 114 different polling booths.
And the most reviewed polling booth was the Department of Primary Industries building, in Brisbane Central, which also offered pre-polling.
The second most reviewed booth was Wellers Hill SS in Yeerongpilly.
14 booths were reviewed three or more times. The four most reviewed booths were, with five reviews, Boondall SS and Ithaca Creek SS.
A few quick piece of data for you all, we received 172 reviews from 114 different polling booths.
